<BlogPost
  title="One App Instead of Three"
  description="Notes, tasks, and calendar belong together. Pikos puts them in one place."
  date="2026-04-05"
>

  <p>
    Most people manage their work across at least three apps. A notes app for writing things down. A task manager for tracking what needs to get done. A calendar for scheduling when it happens. Each app is fine on its own, but together they create a constant switching tax — copy the meeting notes into the task app, link the task to the calendar, check the calendar to remember what you wrote in the notes app.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pikos puts all three in one window.
  </p>

  <h2>How it works</h2>

  <p>
    In Pikos, everything is a page. A page can be a note, a task, or a calendar event — or all three at once. Write meeting notes, mark it as in progress, schedule it for Thursday. It shows up in your note list, your task view, and your calendar. One thing, one place.
  </p>

  <p>
    You don't have to decide upfront whether something is a "note" or a "task." Start writing, and add structure as you need it — set a due date, assign a priority, move it to a folder. Or don't. A page with no metadata is just a note, and that's fine.
  </p>

  <h2>The calendar is built in</h2>

  <p>
    The calendar isn't a separate mode you switch to. It's a panel that lives alongside your editor. Toggle it open, and you see your week. Drag a page onto a time slot to schedule it. Click a time slot to create a new page. Your notes and your schedule are always one glance apart.
  </p>

  <h2>Quick capture</h2>

  <p>
    Press a keyboard shortcut and a small dialog pops up. Type something like "Call dentist tomorrow high priority" and Pikos parses it — creates a page titled "Call dentist," schedules it for tomorrow, sets the priority to high. You don't have to click through dropdown menus or fill out forms. Just type what you're thinking.
  </p>

  <h2>Who this is for</h2>

  <p>
    Pikos is for people who are tired of bouncing between apps to manage their day. If you want one place to write things down, track what's pending, and see what's coming up — without creating accounts, syncing services, or paying monthly — this is that app.
  </p>

  <p>
    It's not trying to replace Notion for team wikis or Jira for engineering sprints. It's a personal tool. Your notes, your tasks, your calendar, your device.
  </p>

</BlogPost>
